</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Calendar; Page 32; Calendar Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
359 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
CINEFILE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KIRK HONEYCUTT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Billy Crystal, Rick Moranis and Bruno Kirby play three pals who take time off 
from their high-pressure New York City jobs to go on a week-long cattle drive 
across Wyoming in Castle Rock's "City Slicker." Ron Underwood directs this 
Lowell Ganz-Babaloo Mandel screenplay about life, friendship and cows beginning 
late August in Santa Fe, N.M.. Irby Smith produces while Crystal executive 
produces. 
</P>
<P>
Ellen Burstyn will star opposite Martin Landau in Christina Pictures' romantic 
drama "The Color of Evening," which producer/director Stephen Thomas Stafford 
starts shooting July 30 in Southern California. Burstyn plays the model who 
inspires an aging painter in both art and love. 
</P>
<P>
Danish producer Just Betzer, winner of the best foreign film Oscar for 1987's 
"Babette's Feast," is set to launch two films through his Los Angeles-based 
Jube Films. In "Newman," getting under way in L.A. this month, Tony Cookson 
directs his own screenplay about two boys who invent a robot to help their 
struggling widowed mother. Sam Behrens (Danny Waleska on "Knot's Landing") and 
John Quade join previously announced Marcia Strassman, Joshua Miller and Edan 
Gross. Meanwhile, on Sept. 3, Kenneth Madsen will roll cameras in Denmark for 
"A Day in October," starring D. B. Sweeney, Kelly Wolfe Tovah Feldshuh and 
Daniel Benzali Damien F. Slattery's love story is set against the backdrop of 
Denmark's rescue of its Jewish population during Nazi Occupation. 
</P>
<P>
Phoebe Cates and Rick Mayall star in "Drop Dead, Fred," which Paul Webster 
produces for the London-based Working Title Prods. Ate Dejold directs Anthony 
Fingleton and Carlos Davis' screenplay about a woman, about to be married, who 
is visited by her childhood fantasy friend. The independent film gets under way 
in Minnesota Aug. 6. 
</P>
<P>
Bill Pullman joins Kevin Anderson, Pamela Gidley, Kim Novak in Initial Films 
and Pathe's "Liebestraum," currently filming in Binghamton, N.Y. Mike Figgis 
produces (with Eric Fullner and Michael Flynn), wrote and is directing this 
atmospheric drama about an adopted man meeting his birth mother for the first 
time and coming to grips with a long-ago murder. KIRK HONEYCUTT 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Billy Crystal ; Photo, Martin Landau ; Photo, Ellen Burstyn 
</P>
