<HEADLINE>
<P>
OPPOSITE POLES: READERS RAISE MORE BURNING ISSUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Congressman (Robert) Dornan views our nation's flag as "the ultimate expression 
of the Judeo-Christian ethic." Obviously, Dornan does not really understand the 
religions to which he appeals for support in his attempt to prohibit flag 
burning. 
</P>
<P>
While some Christian churches revere icons or relics, all aspects of Judaism 
and most Christian churches oppose the glorification of material objects, 
including flags. Instead of respect for material objects, Judeo-Christian 
ethics teach respect for ideals and principles, such as the liberties found in 
our nation's Constitution. 
</P>
<P>
Some of the opposition to the constitutional amendment that would have banned 
flag burning had nothing to do with civil liberties. Instead, religious 
opposition feared an attempt to deify the flag. After all, how can you 
desecrate something unless it is first declared sacred? 
</P>
<P>
DAVID E. ROSS 
</P>
<P>
Agoura 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
