<HEADLINE>
<P>
A MISTAKE? NOT REALLY! 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the interesting article "Weaving Through Scot Isle" (Travel Section, May 
20), Beverly Beyer and Ed Rabey state: "Whiskey is spelled this way in Britain, 
and it always means Scotch." 
</P>
<P>
They are only half right. It is true that whisky always means Scotch in 
Britain, but it is always spelled whisky. Never whiskey. 
</P>
<P>
PETER HUME 
</P>
<P>
El Toro 
</P>
<P>
 Editor's Note: According to the Los Angeles Times Style Book, when referring 
to Scotch or Canadian liquors, the word is spelled with an "e", as in whiskey 
or whiskeys. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
