<HEADLINE>
<P>
GOVERNMENT STING USED AGAINST WASHINGTON'S MAYOR BARRY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The smoke-screen claims of racism and law enforcement overkill to explain the 
Mayor Barry sting are missing the main point of the government's extraordinary 
but necessary efforts to arrest Barry, who at the time of his arrest was the 
No. 1 law enforcement officer in the District of Columbia. To catch a big 
criminal fish the government's legal net has to be larger and stronger than one 
required to arrest and convict an ordinary criminal. No ordinary police officer 
could walk in and arrest Richard Nixon for conspiracy, or Michael Milken for 
fraud. The status and power of the alleged offender has to factor into the law 
enforcement effort necessary to bring the offender to justice. 
</P>
<P>
For example, the legal process for attempting to convict the criminal 
conspiracies of Richard Nixon required the entire Congress and even the Supreme 
Court. Despite all of this legal firepower Nixon eluded being convicted when 
his deal with his selected President, Gerald Ford, resulted in his 
comprehensive pardon. Former President Reagan (who no longer remembers the 
alleged criminal offenses committed within the context of the Boland 
Amendment), and President Bush because of their political positions and power 
have eluded the criminal net for their alleged crimes in the Iran-Contra mess. 
Former U.S. Atty. Gen. Edwin Meese through various legal maneuvers managed to 
avoid prosecution for various deviant acts he committed in his powerful 
position. It is simply more difficult to arrest and convict people in power, 
who control some of the legal machinery that is in place to deal with their 
crimes, than ordinary offenders. 
</P>
<P>
In Barry's case, it should not be forgotten, that in an earlier effort to 
apprehend him for using drugs in a hotel (a criminal act testified to by 
several witnesses), the police in Barry's police department were called off at 
the last moment. Power-status crimes require extraordinary and powerful police 
and judicial procedures for the effective administration of justice. 
</P>
<P>
LEWIS YABLONSKY 
</P>
<P>
Professor of Criminology 
</P>
<P>
Cal State Northridge 
</P>
</TEXT>
