671 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
GENEROUS REWARDS TO TREASURE HUNTERS HELP INDONESIA KEEP ITS ART; 
</P>
<P>
ANTIQUITIES: AN EXHIBIT TOURING THE U.S. SHOWS THE WISDOM OF A NATION'S PAYING 
MARKET VALUE FOR FINDS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CARL HARTMAN, ASSOCIATED PRESS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Indonesia may have a lesson to teach other countries that are rich in buried 
ancient art. 
</P>
<P>
In such places, looters often sell artifacts to private dealers rather than 
turn them over to the authorities. In Indonesia, however, the authorities 
compete with private collectors by rewarding finders generously. 
</P>
<P>
A show that opened this month at the National Gallery of Art displays many 
treasures that came to the Indonesian government because of this system. 
</P>
<P>
One of the treasures was found in a cave on the island of Java by archeologists 
helping the government survey tourist sites. 
</P>
<P>
Jan Fontein of the Boston Museum of Fine Arts, who put the show together, 
described the find: " . . . inside the cave filled with stalagmites and 
stalactites, on top of a tall rock shaped like an altar, they discovered a 
large bronze vessel containing several objects, including this gold and silver 
statuette of a couple holding hands." 
</P>
<P>
Archeologists calculate that the tiny figures -- less than 5 inches high -- 
must be at least 1,000 years old. They still aren't sure who the subjects 
represented, probably the Hindu god Shiva and his consort, Parvati. 
</P>
<P>
Both are naked from the waist up. Their heads are surrounded by halos and 
protected by little golden parasols. 
</P>
<P>
"The Sculpture of Indonesia" exhibit, in Washington through Nov. 4, will also 
travel to Houston, New York and San Francisco. Many of its best items were 
found by chance. 
</P>
<P>
A much bigger Shiva -- more than 42 inches high -- in gold, bronze and silver 
and with four arms and three eyes, was found in 1933 by farmers bathing in the 
Kali Wadas River. 
</P>
<P>
Fontein has counted 854 separate finds, some of which include several objects. 
They were reported to Dutch authorities before Indonesia became independent, 
and since then to the Indonesian government and other official bodies. 
</P>
<P>
"There's a tendency to report them because of the fair way the authorities 
reward the finders," he told a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
In many parts of the world finders get more by selling their treasures secretly 
than they would if they reported them. That enrages museums and archeologists 
because thieves and amateurs often destroy much of the evidence, sometimes 
unwittingly. 
</P>
<P>
Fontein told of a boy working in an Indonesian garden last year who found a 
gold neckpiece that weighed more than 3 1/2 pounds. He said the authorities 
paid the full market price of the gold and divided it between the boy and owner 
of the garden. 
</P>
<P>
"The boy's education is assured," he added. 
</P>
<P>
Fontein was allowed to see the neckpiece on condition that he did not ask for 
it to be sent to the exhibition. An attempt will be made to film it for a 
production linked with an 18-month celebration of Indonesian culture that is to 
open here in September. 
</P>
<P>
J. Carter Brown, director of the National Gallery, said the exhibit opened 
before September because so many people visit Washington in summer. 
</P>
<P>
Fontein said he did not know why so many objects were buried. Many of them were 
found close to the surface. One farmer found a temple bell in a field when 
planting a new kind of sugar cane required him to plow a few centimeters 
deeper. Near it was a box with a chain from which the bell had been hung. 
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes I think they buried them just for us to find," he said. 
</P>
<P>
Faithful Buddhists and Hindus buried many things when Indonesia was invaded by 
Muslims 400 years ago. The Muslims disapproved of human images and 
representations of living things and objects connected with other religions. 
</P>
<P>
Buddhists and Hindus took refuge in the hills of Java. The final object in the 
show is a three-panel sculpture, apparently of Hindu origin. It is more than 5 
feet high and 7 feet long and shows a scene in a blacksmith's shop. On one side 
is the smith forging a sword. On the other is a man working a bellows to heat 
the forge. 
</P>
<P>
In the center panel is a fat man with the head of an elephant, naked and 
dancing. He is wearing a priest's headdress and holding a small dog in one 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
What is he doing there? That story is lost. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The Hindu god Siva Mahadeva, above, a bronze, gold and silver statue 
dating from 900, and the Goddess of Transcendental Wisdom, right, a stone 
carving from 1300, are in "The Sculpture of Indonesia" exhibit at the National 
Gallery of Art in Washington. United Press International 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
