<HEADLINE>
<P>
GALANTER OFFERS PLAN TO SAVE SAND DUNES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIM WATERS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Los Angeles City Councilwoman Ruth Galanter proposed Friday that 200 acres of 
ecologically sensitive sand dunes at the west end of Los Angeles International 
Airport's runways be turned into a nature preserve. 
</P>
<P>
Flanked by a handful of supporters at the site and fighting to be heard as 
jumbo jets screamed overhead, Galanter said the airport should abandon its 
long-stalled plan to convert about 200 acres of the 302-acre dunes into a golf 
course. 
</P>
<P>
Rather, Galanter said, the airport should use only 100 acres of the dunes, best 
known as a habitat for the endangered El Segundo Blue butterfly, for the golf 
course. The airport could complete the course by using another 50 acres it owns 
next to the dunes on the north side of LAX, she said. 
</P>
<P>
"We can have the butterfly and we can have the golfers," Galanter said. 
</P>
<P>
Galanter's proposal has not been formally presented to other council members or 
to the city Airport Commission. Clifton Moore, general manager of the Airport 
Department, said he and Galanter have discussed her proposal in general terms 
but not in detail. 
</P>
<P>
"We have indicated we will keep an open mind and talk about it," Moore said. 
</P>
<P>
Galanter's plan to use 50 acres on the airport's north side for a golf course 
clashes with the airport's plan to use the land as part of a large office and 
research park development. The parcel is part of 350 acres once dotted with 
homes that were acquired by the airport because of severe jet noise. 
</P>
<P>
Donald Miller, the airport's deputy executive director, said work has already 
began on a four-lane highway for the office park project, which is to extend 
from Sepulveda Eastway to Pershing Drive. The airport recently received final 
approval from the city for the development to proceed, he said. 
</P>
<P>
Galanter contends that most of the land for the office project will be paved 
for parking lots. By redesigning the project and building underground parking 
structures, she said, 50 acres could be found for the golf course. 
</P>
<P>
The dunes that Galanter wants to protect are the last large section of a dune 
system that once stretched from Point Conception, above Santa Barbara, south to 
Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
The airport began work to establish a habitat for the El Segundo Blue butterfly 
on the dunes in the late 1970s, shortly after the insect was classified as 
endangered by the federal government. About five years ago, the airport 
proposed using 200 acres of the dunes for a golf course and turning the rest 
into a nature preserve. 
</P>
<P>
That plan was stalled in 1987 when the California Coastal Commission refused to 
give the airport permission to move ahead because it was unclear what effect 
the golf course would have on the butterfly. 
</P>
<P>
Airport officials hired scientist Rudy Mattoni to do a biological study of the 
dunes to determine the golf course's effect. Mattoni's study identified at 
least nine insects, including the El Segundo Blue butterfly, and a flower that 
apparently live only on the dunes and could be classified as endangered. 
</P>
<P>
Mattoni, who supports Galanter's plan, said the butterfly is now flourishing on 
the dunes. If 200 acres of the dunes are preserved, he said, the entire dune 
ecosystem would have a better chance of surviving. 
</P>
<P>
"We're trying to preserve the whole ecosystem, this whole community of 
interactions," Mattoni said. "I'm not worried about the butterfly; I am worried 
about everything else." 
</P>
<P>
Mattoni's study found that native plant and animal life on the dunes has been 
seriously affected over the years by development and soil contamination, which 
in turn have allowed non-native species to invade the area. 
</P>
<P>
Of the 20 original mammals believed to have lived on the dunes, only three 
remain, Mattoni said. Of the 91 original plant species, only 58 remain and 19 
are in danger of being eliminated. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, The conflict over dunes near LAX is exemplified at news conference by 
jet flying overhead ED COMPEAN / Los Angeles Times; Photo, and the presence of 
a rare El Segundo Blue butterfly. 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
